did.unittitle:
Account of crops made under James Wilsford
                  for estate of James Macon, 
                  1764.

scopecontent.p:
Asks Charles Campbell how much money he needs;
                     will allow Charles Campbell to continue his
                     studies with Judge Tucker.

Concerned about Charles Campbell's health;
                        business has been better than usual;
                        subscriptions for a railroad from Wilkins Ferry
                        to Belfield being taken, but "our citizens will
                        be cautious about buying more railroad stock"
                        since the old stock has fallen in value.

Received Charles Campbell's order for books;
                        not sure he will continue selling books; small
                        pox epidemic.

Has gotten married; brother and sister well;
                        father still selling books; thinking of moving
                        to Missouri.

Hopes Henleys will visit wants to meet
                        Charles Campbell's wife; news of her studies;
                        news of her brothers and sisters.

Death of his father; 
                        Lavinia
                        [Moore?]being sent to the aunt.

About buying a slave; yellow fever epidemic;
                        asks Charles Campbell's mother to visit his
                        wife.

Misses her; glad she is going to school;
                        hopes she will not hurry into marriage; misses
                        William.

Asks about medical school in Richmond;
                        father is blind; brother Samuel is a preacher;
                        brother Charles is "a sort of an Abolitionist;
                        brother William is a successful politician.

Fears his work would be a "losing business";
                        advises him not to make it "too
                        voluminous".

Family news; asks about Francis V. Sutton;
                        Lavinia's marriage failed; Locos are praising
                        Tyler and Whigs cursing him.

Has met Charles Campbell's Henley cousins;
                        plans to marry Elizabeth Henley in May; Whigs
                        elected in Tennessee.

Is preparing a "Geography of Virginia";
                        Charles Campbell's Bland Papers "a failure";
                        asks for information on Virginia.

Money from Charles Campbell's son's estate;
                        Disposition of the estate's slaves; Family
                        news.

Hope to have his book in press by November;
                        he hopes to have it well-illustrated. Asks some
                        questions about early Virginia history.

Will meet Charles Campbell in Richmond;
                        hopes Powhatan's chimney still stands; Randolph
                        Will Case still in court.

Thanks him for his news of movements in the
                        Revenue Department. Clerkship has been offered;
                        will probably be in Petersburg.

Parents are dead and household broken up; is
                        teaching at the academy with Edward Caruthers;
                        is leaving for Missouri.

Visited her old house; Robert Moore dead;
                        invites her to visit; church convention open in
                        May; many beaux in Petersburg.

Enjoyed the 
                        Bland Papers;
                        hopes he will visit.

Asks him to return the copy of Stith to Mr.
                        Robins; will publish his own history soon;
                        hopes to get a copy of Smith.

Patrick Henry anecdote; would like to visit;
                        will send a copy of his book to cousin Sally;
                        "Petersburg is of all places the hottest and
                        dullest"; asks for tombstone epitaphs.

Plans to send his son west for the summer;
                        would take over guardianship of his son's
                        estate; family news.

Is visiting Uncle Frank; has gone hunting
                        and caught a rabbit and five fish and a dove;
                        will go to Chota with Uncle Tom.

Taught with Charles Campbell at Somerville;
                        news of his brothers-all portrait painters; is
                        postmaster at Aberdeen.

Has been sick; hopes to meet Father at
                        Warrenton; Grandmother's school almost over;
                        cholera epidemic.

Anna Campbell's brother William arrived;
                        Charles Campbell will pick up Anna Campbell in
                        Richmond.

Glad she survived childbirth, but
                        disappointed the child was a girl; is not well;
                        Mother at Trenton; her husband dead.

Mr. Thweat has moved into the house and
                        opened his shop; advice on buying chickens;
                        John W. Rice's forgery mentioned.

Asks for information on Robert Beverley;
                        plans to bring out a new edition of Beverley's 
                        History.

Saw the burning of the Steamboat Cherokee;
                        describes his day in New York City; will join
                        her soon.

Hopes school is going well; baby is well;
                        enjoying the country; thinks Quakers have a
                        useful religion; cousin Mary not well.

Does not expect John Maben to be well again;
                        will visit Chota; does not want his fowls sold;
                        asks for an Express, an Intelligencer, and a
                        South Side.

Is well; wants to hire a servant girl;
                        housecleaning instructions; has been to friends
                        meeting and heard Rachel Barker preach.

Baptists are holding twice-a-day meetings;
                        family news; wheat suffering from Hessian Fly
                        and Chinch Bug.

Family news; went to see the model farm;
                        warns her against using homeopathy or
                        allopathy; worries about her health.

Traveled by water carriage and railroad;
                        visiting in Rahway and enjoying the
                        weather.

Uncle Tom leaving Cleveland for Georgia;
                        Mary McGhee thinking of moving to
                        Cleveland.

Describes a trip to Richmond; family news;
                        visited the new Post Office and Custom House,
                        the Historical Society and State Library.

Mother strained herself cutting down trees;
                        baby had colic; has been sewing; went to
                        church; hopes book will be published.

Local news; has sent back the last proof
                        sheet for his book and is working on the index;
                        it is 751 pages.

Uncle Aleck a Fire-Eater and Secessionist;
                        Callaway is unionist; Mary McGhee [M. K.
                        Henley] married again.

Is harvesting wheat; Camp Pickens is nearby;
                        expects a battle soon; expects South to win;
                        belongs to a volunteer company; "money-loving
                        Yankees" will give up soon.

Thanks her for her care of his son Robert;
                        gives advice on advising Robert; hopes the war
                        will be over soon.

Has no post office; main body of the army did
                     not go through his area; many towns being rebuilt;
                     negroes are being treated badly by the troops;
                     Callaway fears the negroes will not be able to
                     take care of themselves; has not married.

Teaching the children reading and sewing;
                        Charles Campbell should put his faith in God to
                        provide; is reading the Gospels.

Acknowledges receipt of news of Mother's
                        condition. Son Johnny now in Philadelphia;
                        other children attending school.

Thank you note; has been confined to the house;
                     hopes Mrs. Campbell will recover from the effects
                     of her fall; would like to see Mary and Nanny.

Minutes of the Ladies Club of Washington Street
                  Church, Petersburg, for soldiers relief, 1861 July
                  1-July 27; 

"Diary of the War", 1863 June 28-1864 July 22; 

Charles Campbell: Journal, 1861 April 22-May 4;

Journal, 1862 July 16-August 3; 

Index to diaries by date #1-9.

Inventory of Rahway house contents, 1848-1851;
                  cash receipts and disbursements ledger, 1863-1867;
                  accounts for Anderson Seminary shoe purchases, 1863;
                  extracts from letters; Burdsall & Co. accounts,
                  1848.
